73":"1173","1161":"1161","20 August 1253":"20 August 1253","1180":"1180","Woodham Walter, Essex, England":"Woodham Walter, Essex, England","Hexham, Northumberland, England":"Hexham, Northumberland, England","Colton, Staffordshire, England":"Colton, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Baynard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>Bainard</i>, via Norman French from ancient Germanic <i>Beinhard</i>, perhaps from <i>bein-</i> ‘leg, bone’ or a supposed element <i>bagin-</i> ‘dispute’ + <i>-hard</i> ‘hard, brave’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bainer","meanings":["English: perhaps a late development of   Baynard  , with loss of the final <i>d</i>. The earliest record found of this name in Britain, spelled <i>Bayner</i>, is dated 1546."]},{"name":"Bunyard","meanings":["English (Kent, of Norman origin): variant of   Baynard  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Baynard was born in 1180, in Woodham Walter, Essex, England, United Kingdom. He married Dina FitzRobert in 1197, in Colton, Staffordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 10 April 1258, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1180–10 April 1258":"1180–10. aprill 1258","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","1161–1253":"1161–1253","1198–1225":"1198–1225","1180–1258":"1180–1258","after 1225":"pärast 1225","1258":"1258","1225":"1225","10 April 1258":"10. aprill 1258","1198":"1198","1253":"1253","1197":"1197","1173":"1173","1161":"1161","20 August 1253":"20. august 1253","1180":"1180","Woodham Walter, Essex, England":"Woodham Walter, Essex, England","Hexham, Northumberland, England":"Hexham, Northumberland, England","Colton, Staffordshire, England":"Colton, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"1180–10 April 1258":"1180–10. huhtikuuta 1258","1173–Female":"1173–Kuollut","1161–1253":"1161–1253","1198–1225":"1198–1225","1180–1258":"1180–1258","after 1225":"1225 jälkeen","1258":"1258","1225":"1225","10 April 1258":"10. huhtikuuta 1258","1198":"1198","1253":"1253","1197":"1197","1173":"1173","1161":"1161","20 August 1253":"20. elokuuta 1253","1180":"1180","Woodham Walter, Essex, England":"Woodham Walter, Essex, England","Hexham, Northumberland, England":"Hexham, Northumberland, En